is used in a patient population that was either not receiving any surgical 
therapy due to extreme risk or was considered very high risk for conventional 
surgery. The procedure requires a highly trained TAVR team, advanced imaging, 
and the devices themselves, which are expensive. Medical device trials are 
generally designed to establish if the device works as planned. For TAVR in 
today's world of rising health care costs, the additional question of cost 
effectiveness is important to address. Fortunately, the PARTNER trial addressed 
this and the CoreValve trial has built this into the trial design as well. This 
article examines what is currently known about the cost-effectiveness of TAVR.

